</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="258" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,223,465]" pageId="13" pageNumber="258">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1862" box="[151,277,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Synlestidae" genus="Megalestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="13" pageNumber="258" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,277,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="258">Megalestes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a group of large damselflies. The body length usually ranges from 
<quantity box="[1057,1202,223,250]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.25" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="6.5" pageId="13" pageNumber="258" unit="mm" value="72.5" valueMax="80.0" valueMin="65.0">65 to 80 mm</quantity>
, and the wing length ranges from 
<quantity box="[291,435,259,286]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.75" metricValueMax="4.5" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="13" pageNumber="258" unit="mm" value="37.5" valueMax="45.0" valueMin="30.0">30 to 45 mm</quantity>
. Wings are obviously petiolate and usually outspread at 180° when resting. Wing venation is relatively sparse, with the 
<emphasis box="[470,498,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="258">mf</emphasis>
close to 
<emphasis box="[597,633,296,321]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="258">arc</emphasis>
rather than to 
<emphasis box="[795,862,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="258">nodus</emphasis>
. Structures of caudal appendages and genital ligula are simple, with cerci usually longer and more robust than the paraprocts. All species in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1862" box="[1144,1270,331,357]" class="Insecta" family="Synlestidae" genus="Megalestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="13" pageNumber="258" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1144,1270,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="258">Megalestes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have the same ecological and biological features. They occur in slowly moving montane springs or brooks with dense vegetation. Since the number of studied specimens was large, we placed all of the information concerning “Material examined” into 
<tableCitation box="[201,285,439,465]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,239,468,494]" captionText="TABLE 1. List of examined and analyzed specimens. Specimens with ID numbers were used for molecular analysis, and L indicates larva." pageId="13" pageNumber="258">Table 1</tableCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
